.TH CAT(1),User Commands,CAT(1)

.SH NAME
cat - concatenate and print files

.SH SYNOPSIS
cat [file ...]

.SH DESCRIPTION
cat reads each file in sequence and writes its contents to standard output.
If no file operands are given, cat reads from standard
input one byte at a time until end-of-input.

Files are processed in the order given on the command line.
If a file cannot be opened,
cat prints an error message identifying the file and the error code, then continues with the next file.

Unlike the typical POSIX cat, no formatting options
(numbering, visible characters, etc.) are supported.

.SH EXAMPLES
Print a single file:

$ cat /etc/motd

Concatenate multiple files:

$ cat header.txt body.txt

Echo standard input:

$ cat

.SH EXIT STATUS
cat exits 0 after processing all operands, regardless of whether individual files failed to open.
